Assignment 1.1 Paper Prototype


Introduction


In this assignment, we were tasked to create a quick paper prototype of a ﬁtness tracking device that connects with the phone app. The minimum requirements of the app features are:


  • Start/stop tracking based on the user's input

  • Tracking of burned calories, distance traveled, and current user speed in a real-time display of this data to the user

  • Display report of past tracked data per day/week/month


    The paper prototype

    These screens are per day/week/month data for the user on the smartwatch


    This is the ﬁrst idle screen where it shows the user the current time and can be tapped to show the main menu of the watch in the picture below


    The fitness tracker app main menu which you can access the daily meters ran

    Fitness tracker app's main menu you can access the average speed

    Fitness tracker app's main menu you can access the calories burnt.


    This is the ﬁtness tracker app paper prototype. Unlike the smart watch's interface, I made the ﬁtness tracker app with just the function for daily reports of the past 4 days instead of the other weekly and monthly reports displayed on the watch. As you can see, the user can click on one of the 3 options of "Meters ran", "Average speed" or "Kcal burned" to expand the report to show them in their previous days. On the day we created the prototype it was the 9th of February so it showed 2 previous days that the user had exercised.


    Feedback


    I tested this ﬁrst paper prototype with Ruud, our BEP lecturer. The main purpose of this ﬁrst test was to gain feedback from him about the basic functionalities and screens of the watch and app. Throughout the test, he mentioned that the app works well and properly however, there are some improvements that can be made to the layout and UI of the screens as it doesn't seem to be very learnable. Taking this feedback into account, the UI design of the daily/weekly/monthly reports could be expanded for easier comprehension for the user. Daily/Weekly/Monthly reports screens shown on the watch and app could be expanded to other pages by separating each data(kcal, average speed, and meters ran) to be on other newly created screens which will make it easier to read and more detailed for an ideal ﬁtness user.


    Short reﬂection


    This was the ﬁrst assignment of the BEP course and I also felt like it is the toughest as I was all new to prototyping. This assignment felt hard, especially in the parts where you actually had to measure/cut out the paper or cardboard

    correctly to match the dimensions. In addition, it was quite weird and new to me to build something physical out of scratch.


    Assignment 1.2 Non-visual Prototyping


    Introduction


    This week G assignment was all about non-visual prototyping, mainly to present core functionalities of the design(previous week's application) with main sounds. In this assignment, we were tasked to create sound effects for functions of the applications of the ﬁtness tracker using any type of sound. The requirement was to create sound effects for

  • Start/stop tracking

  • Go faster/slower

  • Sip some water

  • Exercise complete or milestone reached

    We are supposed to ﬁnd sound effects or make sound effects that would match these functions, however, if we are to use any soundbanks, we must change the sound effect in some way and not copy it 100%. Since the functions of this week's assignments are different from the ones in the previous week(paper prototype), there was no need to build another visual prototype to match this non-visual prototype. The purpose was just to purely get knowledge about how we could create our own sounds.


    Non-visual Prototype


    At ﬁrst in the workshop studio, I used instruments such as my water bottle or pen to interact with the surrounding environment to test out sounds. There were some tapping sounds that could be used for the functionalities that were created by tapping a laptop part with a pen or sliding a metal piece with the table for indicating going faster or slower.


    Link of all sound effects created: https://ﬁles.fm/u/4na6gbvsy

    All these sounds are named by their functions with one audio ﬁle that is just sound effects that I’ve made during the process but wasn’t chosen for the ﬁtness app functions.


    Feedback


    Most feedback that I’ve received in this week's assignment seems to be very biased and heavily based on personal preference, however, it doesn’t mean that there were any useful ones. Since these types of non-visual sound prototyping can be extremely vague and varied with different types of sounds that anyone

    can use. I mainly tried to carry out interview questions to gather feedback on how the sound could be improved instead of asking for the overall thoughts of the participants. Questions asked during an informal interview:

    1. Overall, how do the sounds you’ve heard match with the functionalities given?

    2. Could you think of any ideas to improve the sounds effects of certain functionalities that would make it easier for other people to perceive ( eg. people with hearing problems)?

    3. Would you like to change the bass or tunes of any of the sounds effects? If yes, how?

    During the quick informal interview, most of the participants agreed with the choices made, and wouldn't want to change the sound effects themselves. However, there was one participant who felt increasing the bass of certain sound effects like the exercise complete sound would help people with hearing problems. Additionally, some others argued whether or not the sound effect of going faster/slower should be shortened or remained the same. Taking this feedback into account, I would increase the bass of the exercise complete sound to help people with hearing problems as the exercise complete is one of the most important functions for someone to notice(because it affects your time and exercise overall if you mess up the timing).


    Short reﬂection


    This assignment was fun and very creativity-inspiring. I really enjoyed exploring the surrounding environment to test out sounds and how objects interact with each other was pretty interesting.


    Assignment 2.1 Wireframe


    Introduction


    The 3rd week’s assignment transitions from working in a physical environment to create prototypes to creating low-ﬁ prototypes on apps. The subject of this week’s assignment was to create a sign-up process wireframe, and the challenge was to make this prototype engaging and fun for the user even though it is low-ﬁ. Here is the list of requirements of functionalities that must be included in the wireframes:

    1. Welcome screen

    2. Gather the following personal information

      1. First and second name (and/or username)

      2. Email

      3. Password (be sure to inform yourself about certain conventions when designing for such critical security features)

    3. Waiting screen (at least 10 seconds)

    4. Feel free to add other elements depending on your chosen platform

    The challenge is to make this wireframe’s sign-up process especially loading screens engaging and immersive. We are able to choose an existing process and re-design it or build it from scratch and can recall engagement factors to help with the challenge.


    The wireframe



    This is the ﬁrst screen, a simple welcome page of the wireframe in which it shows the [Platform] which is the website name I chose as well as its logo. In the background will be slideshows of picture previews of the contents of the websites. For example, the website I wanted to make is for a tournament sign-up website in which esports players compete, so there will be a slideshow of all recent tournament events.

    To continue after the user clicks on the log-in option on the previous page, it will bring the user to this sign up page. It will just be a basic sign up page with the 3 main contents to sign up(username/email/password) and the same background to keep the user’s engaged and interested to know more about the pictures.


    Finally, when the user clicks on the create button, it will continue with a fun loading page where the user sees other pictures of the website but different from the previous two pages. In addition, during other courses, we learned that giving the user a progress indicator as well as acknowledging the user’s action(in this case, signing up) will greatly increase the immersion factor and keep the user’s engaged, hopefully satisﬁed.

    Feedback


    After creating this low-ﬁ wireframe, I conducted 4 quick tests with some of my classmates about the overall content of it. The main intention was to ﬁgure out other ideas or ways that could keep the users engaged further. For this week, our lecturer said we didn’t have to create any iteration as we will have to work on this further to convert it to a high-ﬁ wireframe in the next. Because of this, most of the feedback I had received included cool design improvements that could be made for the high-ﬁ such as choosing engaging photos, and a smart colour scheme to match the website’s theme(eg. Use blue colour if the website focuses on water sports).


    Short reﬂection


    This assignment wasn’t too bad however, the design challenge did make it actually challenging and interesting to develop the wireframe. Speaking of wireframes, we had already learned to make them in the previous semester's courses so it was ﬁne for me, however, I tend to make things in great detail and put effort into small details which conﬂicted with low-ﬁ prototypes.


    Assignment 2.2 High-ffidelity prototype


    Introduction


    Expanding on the previous wireframe assignment, this week, we were assigned to develop that low-ﬁ prototype into a high-ﬁdelity one that included small details and cool design that we wanted to include as well as using colours or sounds for engagement factors.


    High-ffidelity prototype

    Overview of all pages/screens of high-ﬁ prototype made in Figma. Contrary to the wireframe, after all the feedback from it, I chose to change the positions of certain elements of the page as well as add sound effects to it.


    To start off with the welcome screen, I chose a match colour scheme with the background picture which was dark grey and blue. The picture depicts a winning moment of an esports group that I felt was suitable to choose to introduce the website. When the user clicks on the “Login” button, it will transition to the next page with a *Swoosh* sound.



    The next set of screens is the signup process pages where the user can insert their username, email, and password to create their account. The user can click on the white blank box to ﬁll in their credentials and each of those clicks will make a *click* sound.


    After clicking on the blank box in the password section, and ﬁlling it in, the user will most likely enter it incorrectly as the system requires a special character(like ! or @ or and etc) and the user can click on it again to re-enter their password. I made the error message a red colour (different from the background) and put it at the bottom of the password box to make it easier for the user to see it as learned from other courses, their fovea will only focus on that part. When clicking the create button, the same *Swoosh* sound from the welcome screen will play.

    Transitioning to the loading screen, I kept the progress indicator for the user as well as added a red(not error) message which is important for the user that states: “Our employees will never ask for your password, be careful” to warn the users about keeping their own personal security to themselves.


    We go to the ﬁnal screen where the system welcomes and congratulates the user for taking their time to sign-up for the website’s services and informs them that their account is ofﬁcially opened.


    Feedback

    I played the Figma prototype through a link I sent to my classmates to seek out feedback from them. The main testing involved asking about their opinions about the content of the prototype as well as any changes that they would personally make to improve the user experience. Some notable comments I’ve heard about it were:

  • To include some cool swiping animations instead of just a simple click to sign up

  • To create a small and simple game during the loading screen to make it more engaging

  • To allow the user’s to choose their own colour schemes from a set of them such as red/white, black/white, gold/black, etc.

    Taking this feedback into account, I would like to implement some new mouse-triggered animations and the ability to change colour schemes on the prototype to make it more immersive and engaging


    Short reﬂection


    The high-ﬁdelity prototype was amazing to create as I had the freedom to add plenty of fun elements to the previous wireframe. There was no limit to details and elements that we could implement so which made it easier and quicker to create.


    Assignment of week 5/6: Exploratory prototype


    Introduction


    In this 2-week assignment, the task is to simulate an exploratory environment to solve a chosen topic with our own created hypothesis using prototyping. We will expand on our chosen topic from 6 options(or you can suggest your own topic):


    1. Gaze following

      Theory: “Users follow the direction that people in pictures are looking at”


    2. Scanning Patterns

      Theory: “Eyetracking visualizations show that users often read Web pages in an F‐shaped pattern: two horizontal stripes followed by a vertical stripe” https://www.nngroup.com/articles/f‐shaped‐pattern‐reading‐web‐content/


    3. Color

      “We’re visually drawn to colour, especially when it’s used strategically to highlight important information or imagery.” https://www.shoutmeloud.com/colours‐psychology‐conversions.html


    4. Peak-end rule

      “People judge an experience largely based on how they felt at its peak (i.e., its most intense point) and at its end, rather than based on the total sum or average of every moment of the experience.” https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peak%E2%80%93end_rule


    5. Serial Position Effect

      “The tendency of a person to recall the ﬁrst and last items in a series best, and the middle items worst.”

      https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serial-position_effect


    6. Picture Superiority Effect. Pictures and images are more likely to be remembered than words. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Picture_superiority_effect


      After choosing a topic, we proceed to ideate a hypothesis statement for the chosen topic which we could test out with the prototype afterward. Here are some examples of hypotheses for other topics:


      • If the water faucet is opened, then the amount of water ﬂowing will increase.


      • If fenders are placed on a bicycle, then the user will stay dry when going through puddles.


      • If a prisoner learns a work skill while in jail, then he is less likely to commit a crime when he is released.


      • If I raise the temperature of a cup of water, then the amount of sugar that can be dissolved in it will be increased.


    After creating the prototype for the topic hypothesis, we will then conduct A/B testing. This means that we will have to make two variations of our prototype, in which both should be almost exactly identical except for 1 element of it.


    Chosen topic & hypothesis statement


    The topic I’ve chosen is the 3rd one on the list which was to create a prototype that uses different variations of colour for the A/B test. The purpose of this test is to research how the users perceive different types of colours and to determine what would be the better contrast option for the product/app. Assuming the user is not colourblind, the hypothesis statement is: “When presented with two call-to-action buttons, the user will most likely click on the one with the higher contrast”


    Exploratory prototype


    To start off, I just create a basic prototype of the ESL website in iPhone dimensions to simulate an actual app that someone would use. Keeping the sound effects, the *Click* sounds will play when the participant clicks on the “Learn more” and “Register!” options.


    Next, we go straight into the colour exploratory test where I placed the two different variations for the A/B test. When they click on the “Register!” option on the previous screen, they will be randomly greeted with one of either of these screens. The difference between the two variations is the contrasts where I chose white colour for high contrast and black for low. Both call-to-action buttons are different in names but I designed their contents to be roughly the same which hopefully will not affect their decision too much.


    In the end, there will be this screen to inform them of the end of the prototype and the A/B test.



    Topic


    Color Exploratory Prototyping


    Hypothesis


    “When presented with two call-to-action buttons, the user will most likely click on the one with the higher contrast”


    Test


    A/B Test


    Variable


    The color contrast between the CTAs


    Test plan


    The plan will be to give the participant the link to the prototype in which they will start the A/B testing. After proceeding through the prototype, I will request them to ﬁll in a survey from google forms that include questions regarding the prototype and relevant information to answer the hypothesis statement.






    Prototype A


    Prototype B


    Screenshot




    Variable


    The contrasts between the 2 choices were switched to ﬁgure out whether users are most likely to click on low or high contrast call-to-actions


    Feedback

    After conducting the tests with 5 of my classmates, I had them ﬁll out 3 simple questions from Google Forms so it’s easier to analyze the data. The ﬁrst question’s intention was to just ask them about their favourite colour to see where they are in the contrast spectrum. 4 of 5 classmates answered blue to be their favourite colour with 1 saying green. This means that they might be biased

    towards bright colours with high contrast. Moving on, the next question asks them about their opinion on which colours would stand out more. Again, all except 1 person chose says that it depends on the website/app/product and general colour scheme that was used. My intention for these ﬁrst 2 questions was to determine whether the participants would give biased answers based on their personal preferences. The ﬁnal question asks them about their choice between the 2 call-to-action buttons, “Exclusive” and “Premium”. Based on the results, shows that the participants chose the black coloured(low-contrast) option, no matter the contents of the subscription. However, there was still 1 person which chose the opposite(white coloured) option which lead me to believe that in these A/B tests of 5 people, there was 1 outlier. To conclude, after analyzing the results, we can say that the hypothesis statement was false, as the majority chose low-contrast colours rather than their high-contrast counterpart.


    Short reﬂection


    During this 2-week assignment, there was so much work and research that had to be done to conduct this “experiment”, but, in the end, it paid off to be very interesting and fun to see the results. Not to mention, reading articles and other studies about different types of topics/theories made me want to try it again and to prove/disprove other fun theories. Al in all, I felt that the A/B testing when well with an interesting and relevant hypothesis but I would want to better improve the immersion factor in these tests to see how the results could change.


    Assignment of week 6/7: Experience prototyping


    Introduction


    The assignment of these 2 weeks was to Work in pairs to create a Wizard of Oz prototype by creating an interactive application that is immersive and fun which you will test on users in week 8. It can be done with literally anything, paper/cardboard, Figma/Adobe XD prototyping or even coded programs with Processing, etc.

    Recommended concepts

  • Playful interface that uses mapping and (fake) camera or other sensory input

  • Work with video projector

  • Interactive animations onto ﬂoors, walls, objects, or even people

  • Use body movement as (fake) input


    Concept

    During this prototype, I worked with Xiaoying Zhang to make and perform our experience prototyping. Our concept, Wire Defuser! is inspired by the “Bomb man” game but we modiﬁed it a bit. Our game involves showing a bunch of bombs on a platform for a couple of seconds, after that, the bombs will disappear and the participant has to “escape” by getting to the end without touching any bombs. For example, we Let the participant stand at the start tile and then show the 💣 3s then let them walk to the ending tile escaping the 💣


    Scenario protocol


    At ﬁrst, the participant will start on the “start tile” of the canvas of 3 x 4. The participant will be shown “bomb” tiles and the “escape/ending” tile. The system will respond in correlation to the user’s inputs. If the user walks on certain tiles, the system will respond.


    For example: If the participant steps on a “bomb” tile, the system plays a bomb exploding sound and animation which shows that the user has failed the escape challenge and he/she will have to retry. Or if the participant manages to walk correctly and get to the ending without touching any of the bombs, the system will congratulate them, showing them the winning screen.


    Interface elements


    We will be designing a prototype through Adobe XD in which we will use to perform the wizard. Elements of the prototype:

  • Bomb tiles

  • Escape tile

  • Starting tile

  • Normal/Safe tiles

  • Trophy

  • Smoke animation to show the blowing up of the bombs

  • Participant as a cartoon stickman


The wizard inputs


The wizard will provide input whenever the participant steps on any tile. For example, the wizard will follow the participant as a cartoon stick that mimics their movements. Every time the participant steps on the bomb tile, the wizard plays the fail/retry screen of the bomb exploding. When the participants reach the end and escape, the wizard will show the victory screen!


Table summary


Experience prototype


We created an Adobe XD prototype for this experience prototyping, and the ﬁrst 2 screens were to instruct the participants on how the game works. After reading, the participant can step on the GO tile with their feet (we will project it down to the ground) to start the game.


The wizard will proceed with the prototype on their laptop when the game starts(participant steps on GO) with the 3-second countdown to get the user hyped up and ready. Afterwards, the system will show 3 bombs or wire defuser as we call it, and will soon disappear into being invisible in which the participant has to memorise the locations and avoid them to escape


The participant will then jump or run from each tile to tile while the wizard follows them in the prototype. Once they get to the end tile where they have escaped, they will win the game.


If the participant fails and steps on the wrong tile with the bomb, the wizard will activate it, simulating an explosion and the participant loses the game.


Video of participant testing: https://vimeo.com/699598999

*Due to limited time and resources that had to be shared with other groups, there wasn’t a lot of testing being done*

could have thought of to make other types of this experience prototyping but we are glad that it turned out well. Even though it was unfortunate that we had limited time to present this fabulous prototype, it was awesome and everyone had fun.


Final reﬂection


Throughout this building engaging prototype course, I have learned several different types of prototyping methods ranging from creating paper prototypes to simulating a Wizard of Oz experience through experience prototyping.


At the start of the course, we started with a paper prototype which I would categorise as the hardest as it was quite new to me. In addition, I felt like my idea of creativity was hindered when trying to create these physical prototypes as I was poor in my major of arts and crafts. The primary of making paper prototypes was to provide users with a physical prototype of what they can expect in a website, app or phone, etc. Although it was extremely time consuming and resource hungry, it is an efﬁcient and effective way to provide users with a physical and tangible item. Looking back at the paper prototype I made, the process of researching and creating the models to be in reasonable dimensions was such a tedious and annoying time. To add to that, being limited by physical resources such as paper and other tools felt like a hindrance when creating the prototype, as I was used to creating ones online through the internet where I could get all, if not most of my resources. After creating this paper prototype, we proceeded to learn to make non-visual prototypes which, in my opinion, was quite interesting and fun to explore around. The non-visual prototyping we focused on was the element of sounds and how we could implement them in our paper prototypes to make it immersive. I chose not to choose any sounds or take any samples from any sound banks and tried to use the environment around me to make them, ranging from trying out sounds from the studio workshop, all the way back to my home. Throughout this week of non-visual prototyping, I had a lot of fun exploring and interacting with the environment to create a bunch of sounds. I would say it was the easiest or less stressful week to create prototypes as you literally can implement any sounds into any function if you have to write tools to edit them, primarily I used Davinci Resolve 17(a video editing software) to modify the sounds I had collected.


Moving on to the next assignment, we started to make low ﬁdelity wireframes ﬁrst and then transitioned to upgrading those wireframes up to high ﬁdelity prototypes ﬁlled with animations, sounds and colours. The wireframes we created are based on basic stereotypical sign-up processes where we will try to turn the loading screen into a fun and engaging one for the user in the high-ﬁdelity prototype later. While creating my wireframe, I always wanted to add colours and other visuals to it so it looks better but I would always have to be reminded that I should consider wireframes as just a very rough draft for the “ﬁnal product”(high-ﬁ prototype) that will be developed afterwards. One of the strengths of wireframing I had experienced is that getting feedback from your wireframes is crucial for the next process of converting it to a high-ﬁ one. The feedback received during the wireframing process will be relevant and important for you to take in before creating that ﬁnal product to be better or even perfect. In my case, the wireframe feedback caused me to

change certain UI designs such as the placements of objects and to consider using other sound effects later on when making the high-ﬁdelity prototype.


The exploratory prototype was very fascinating to research, make, and do A/B testing. It involves choosing a topic to form a hypothesis statement on which we will do A/B testing to prove or disprove the statement. I loved doing case studies back when I did business studies in high school and this felt very similar to experimenting with case studies. Throughout all the topics available, I chose to test prototypes out with different colour contrasts to see how it really affects the user’s decisions. One of the biggest factors to the reason I chose this topic is that we see different types of colours everywhere in UI designs throughout our everyday lifes so I wanted to research them and how are those colour schemes justiﬁed in their designs. After making my hypothesis statement and designing my prototype, I did rapid A/B testing on 5 of my classmates. A/B testing involves testing the user using 2 different variables in the same design to see how they affect their decisions, even if at all. The strengths of this type of testing are the ability to let you test speciﬁc things of your prototype while being a very time efﬁcient method where you can move on to testing other variables(other A/B tests). The A/B tests I conducted were fast but did give me enough relevant information to solve the hypothesis statement formed. I made a Google Forms survey for the participants that I had tested to put the data in graphs and pie charts which makes it easier to analyse the data. I felt great and making this assignment was a very informative way for me to learn and experience the exploratory prototype which I will use for my future ﬁeld of work.


On to the last type of prototyping, the old school Wizard of Oz type of experience prototyping that simulates a controlled environment where the user can interact in real life, physical with your prototype. The experience prototype can be used to test out possible future technologies without building an actual expensive product such as holographic technologies. In addition, this type of prototyping testing can provide unique insights into the users’ actions when interacting with it. However, one major drawback to the prototype could be that the “Wizard” or the “operator” of the prototype will greatly impact the user when testing. This means that the prototype heavily relies on the wizard and the entire test can be messed up if he/she is not ﬁt for the job. During my experience prototype, I paired up with Xiaoying, a classmate in which we created a fun bomb escaping type game through Adobe XD prototype. Our main concept to simulate the fun, engaging and interactive environment, is to project the prototype we made down to the ground where the user can move around to interact with the game. Our wizard will then mimic the users’ movements on the prototype to keep the prototype running smoothly and to simulate conditions based on the users’ actions such as a bomb exploding or escaping the game(winning/beating the game).


As the ﬁnal prototype to make in this course, I was very satisﬁed with the contents of this course and it really felt like we went out with a bang! All the way from creating tedious paper prototypes, to fun and interactive experience ones, it was an extremely informative, and captivating way of teaching and learning. All the contents of this course were helpful for our future UX designers and maybe the only thing I wished the course had more was

interactive, real-life, seminars to introduce us to the contents instead of boring online lectures.
